@benghaziboy 

So when these tests failed in setUp(), they caused lots of other unrelated tests to fail b/c they never ran tearDown and deactivated freezegun (`self.freezer.stop`). 

Decorator usage is better because it ensures cleanup.  However, this has a side-effect of causing `self.now` to equal the frozen time too ('2015-09-25') which I believe was the expectation?  (The class-level decorator means that the base `setUp` methods are included in the frozen time scope, including [assignment of `self.now`](https://github.com/theonion/django-bulbs/blob/master/bulbs/utils/test/__init__.py#L99)).

I don't think this will do the when after the ``_.defer``.  I did a quick test, just to be sure and it was the other way around.  Since ``defer`` doesn't return a promise, it won't wait till it's done.  It'll just get the timer value from ``defer`` and pass that to the ``.when`` right away.  Here's the test I tried:

   var printIt = function(fleh) {
       console.log(fleh);
   };
   $q.when(
       _.defer(printIt, "first")
   ).then(function() {
       console.log("second");
   });

Rather than re-implementing the file reading, how about just:
```
pub fn extra_big_file_bytes() -> Bytes {
  let mut bytes = big_file_bytes();
  bytes.extend(&big_file_bytes());
  bytes
}
```

(Part of me just wants to add more plays to all_the_henries so that it's over 1MB, though :P I'd wager making it all_the_histories would do the job...)

@petrjasek We discussed it, the  thinking was that the size of the ninjs response would potentially  be large if the names were included. 

I think the customer admin permissioning will need to retrieve a complete list of id's and names, I don't think we'd worked out how that would work. 

I guess I can include the names, we can always remove them if it is a problenm

